ought) much esteeme of;
but omitting others, who
have handled this point
before <HI>Vives</HI> and <HI>Martyr,</HI>
both <HI>Talaus</HI> &amp; <HI>Fox</HI> have
of set purpose lately con|futed
this <HI>Blessednesse of
<PB N="6" REF="11">
Aristotles.</HI> And those an|cient,
and excellent men
have long agoe so con+demned
it, that <HI>Gregorie
Nazi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter">nze<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> calls it con|temptible
and base&punc; <HI>Euse+bius</HI>
unreasonable &amp; false&punc;
<HI>Ambrose, Augustine, Ori|gen,
Lactantius, Gregorie Nyssen</HI> call it very fooli<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="2 letters"> in part, and all of them do
fl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter">tly affi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter">me it to be con|trary
to tru<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter">h and piet<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="tech" EXTENT="1 letter">e.
Whose authoritie when
it is confirmed by Christ
